[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Today we’re introducing a new long-video generation model called JoyAI-Echo from JD com’s open-source team Its basic video generation capability is built on the LTX two point three system but it is not quite the same as a normal text-to-video model A normal text-to-video model usually generates around ten seconds'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So let’s first look at one result This is an ultra-long video How long is it? Two minutes and twenty-four seconds Pay attention:'

[00:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is generated in one go In the video a girl is talking to the camera in a room It is not a small ten-second clip It is a long video made up of many continuous shots Some people may ask: why is this video exactly two minutes and twenty-four seconds?'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That is because JoyAI-Echo’s long videos are actually stitched together from multiple shots The official recommended frame count for each shot is two hundred forty-one frames If we calculate it at twenty-five frames per second'

[00:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one shot is about nine point six seconds It supports up to fifteen shots and multiplying that gives us roughly one hundred forty-four seconds which is the two minutes and twenty-four seconds we see here'

[01:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now let’s look at the second example This one is not that long It is a travel vlog we generated by the Rhine River The character stands by the river'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with a city in the background river water, and natural scenery Of course I think the audio quality from LTX two point three still needs optimization Finally let’s look at the third example'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This style is completely different It is a video where Princess Elsa and a monster appear in the same story It is not simply a person talking to the camera It has characters, conflict'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and environmental changes So you’ll notice that the direction of JoyAI-Echo is not to generate a ten-second showoff clip What it really wants to solve is how to connect multiple shots together and generate a long video with sound characters'

[01:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and a story So what exactly is innovative about JoyAI-Echo? I think there are three keywords here The first is long video as we just mentioned The second is audio and video generation together The third is its memory mechanism'

[02:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or what we can call cross-shot memory The biggest problem with long video is not whether each individual segment looks good The real issue is whether each segment can maintain character consistency environment consistency'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'overall color consistency and here, also audio consistency In JoyAI-Echo’s official materials they repeatedly emphasize that it has a special attention mechanism We can call this a paired audio-video memory mechanism'

[02:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In other words it allows later shots to reference earlier results not only visually but also in terms of sound Now let’s talk about how to use this model inside ComfyUI Right now, you have two options'

[02:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The first is the lossless version The second is the simplified version or what we can call the fast version For the lossless version we use an extension recommended by the official team The feature of this version is that it preserves the full precision of the official model'

[03:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The advantage is that the result is closer to the official output The downside is also very direct: the hardware pressure is huge In the official project'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the full model files are already very large The main model is about forty-six gigabytes and the encoder is over twenty gigabytes So overall consumer-grade GPUs basically cannot run it anymore Here'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I’m using an A800 GPU with eighty gigabytes of VRAM To let everyone experience the lossless version I built an image on Youyun Zhisan also known as Compshare Inside this image, all models'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'extensions and the environment have already been set up The workflow is also ready You can directly create an instance with this image and start using it This image also starts automatically Under normal conditions'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'after you create the instance you don’t need to configure it manually Just wait for it to finish launching then use the public network address plus port eight one eight eight to access your ComfyUI In June'

[04:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Youyun Zhisan has a twenty-percent-off promotion so you can keep an eye on that The second route is the simplified version or the fast version It uses a completely different extension This version is more suitable for consumer-grade GPUs'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because it supports quantized models and GGUF models The file sizes are much smaller and the VRAM pressure is much lower But you should know that quantization is not free'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'What it sacrifices is generation quality and stability especially audio quality Let’s first look at the lossless workflow I think there are two workflows you need to understand here The first is a basic workflow'

[04:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and its structure is very simple At the front there is a JoyEcho_ModelLoader which is used to load the main model Then we load the Gemma-3-12B text encoder In this image'

[05:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I have already configured the paths Pay attention here: what you need to provide are the absolute paths So after downloading the model you can place it anywhere Next is the text encoder This node is very important'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It does not ask you to write a normal prompt sentence What you give it is a JSON Inside this JSON there is a prompts array Each item in the array is the prompt for one shot Below that is the JoyEcho_Generate node'

[05:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This node is mainly responsible for actually generating the video segments Pay attention to a few parameters The first is num_frames This is not the total frame count It is the frame count for each shot'

[05:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Another parameter is resolution Pay attention: in this version I do not recommend using a vertical format Then we have the frame rate and I recommend using twenty-five frames per second In the backend'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we can also see this attention mechanism or attention chain From the beginning an attention chain can appear This chain goes from one to seven So if you want to maintain character consistency or audio consistency with minimal deviation I recommend keeping the shot count within eight'

[06:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The Rhine River beauty video and the video of the girl talking in the room were both generated with this workflow So what is this workflow suitable for? If you already have a complete prompt and you have already planned every segment'

[06:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and you just want to generate the whole thing at once then this workflow is the simplest option The lossless version also has another very useful workflow called shot-by-shot generation This one looks much more complicated'

[06:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but the logic is easier to understand It still starts by loading the model Then we have fifteen sets of structures First JoyEcho_PromptAtIndex extracts the prompt needed for the current segment from the full prompt Pay attention here:'

[06:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the index value keeps increasing which means the prompt being extracted is different each time Of course you don’t have to use a full prompt You can also write one shot manually Below that is JoyEcho_SingleShotGenerate'

[07:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which generates the video for one shot Pay attention: after generation besides video and audio there is also memory This memory is passed on to the next segment So the second segment does not start from zero'

[07:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It knows what happened before This is why the shot-by-shot workflow is more suitable for generating long stories Each segment can be previewed individually You can first check whether this segment is correct'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If it is continue generating downward If it is not, you can adjust it It also does not require you to build all prompts at the very beginning The Princess Elsa video we saw earlier was generated with this workflow Next'

[07:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let’s talk about the simplified workflow This one can run but the results have some issues It has four core nodes The first is JoyAI_Echo_SM_Clip This node is mainly responsible for loading the text encoder In this extension'

[08:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can use GGUF or a normal model Here I’m using a Q4 quantized model The second node is JoyAI_Echo_SM_Encoder which is the text encoding node Here I recommend setting prefetch_count to one'

[08:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If your VRAM is especially large you can set it to zero If your VRAM is not enough you need to use it together with modes like swap and streaming The third node is JoyAI_Echo_SM_Model'

[08:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It also gives you two options: you can load a normal model or you can load a GGUF model The fourth node is JoyAI_Echo_SM_KSampler which is the sampler For resolution'

[08:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I recommend using twelve eighty by seven thirty-six Here I used something slightly lower nine sixty by five forty-four There is also a parameter here that is easy to misunderstand: num_frames'

[08:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Again this is not the total frame count It is the frame count for each shot The advantage of the simplified version is that each model is not that large so consumer-grade GPUs can run it But based on my testing'

[09:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it still has some issues right now The first issue is that subtitles can easily appear The second issue is that at the beginning of the video it is very easy for a male character in ancient costume to appear I tested this many times'

[09:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is not occasional It appears very easily and very commonly I don’t know whether it is caused by default prompt conditions in the model or by some kind of cache For now'

[09:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'my handling method is very simple: I directly cut off the extra beginning part Compared with the lossless version the overall quality is indeed much lower The visuals are still acceptable but the audio is much worse'

[09:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There can be very messy electronic noise especially when the story is more complex Some people may ask: what is the most important thing about this model? I can tell you clearly: it is definitely not the workflow So what is it?'

[09:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It is the prompt Writing the prompt directly affects how well the attention mechanism works Every shot needs to be written very completely Roughly speaking you should write it like this First, start with ID_'

[10:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then use A B, C, D to represent characters For example we can write ID_A to represent one character This is why JoyAI-Echo prompts are especially long As long as the same character is involved'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we need to rewrite similar information again to strengthen the memory mechanism To lower the barrier the official team provides two prompt-engineering templates One is called Short Story Writer'

[10:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is suitable for generating a single shot The second is called Long Story Writer which is suitable for generating long videos By default it generates fifteen shots We can put this into a large model and let the model generate the prompt for us'

[10:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So which large model should we use? I had a sudden idea and tested three very famous tools Actually we shouldn’t call them large models here We should call them web coding tools'

[11:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The first is Codex The second is Claude The third is Antigravity Many people are probably very familiar with these tools The theme I tested was this: a person travels into the world of Journey to the West and as a firsthand participant'

[11:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'records clips of the Havoc in Heaven on a phone The whole thing is in a vlog format Many people have seen this kind of concept before because in Seedance two point zero a lot of people use it this way and the generated results are pretty good'

[11:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But not many open-source models can do this well so we let JoyAI-Echo try it Similarly each video has fifteen shots It needs complete character settings scenes from Eastern mythology'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'action, audio camera movement, and shot pacing In the end, we got three videos We mainly evaluate them from four angles The first is Eastern aesthetics: can it write things like the Heavenly Palace'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sea of clouds, immortal palaces and the Peach Garden with a Chinese mythological feeling? The second is whether key characters appear such as Sun Wukong the Heavenly Court'

[12:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and immortals The third is whether the key characters’ features are accurate The fourth is whether the vlog perspective works My conclusion is that Claude and Codex are both pretty good overall Claude performs very well when describing the sky'

[12:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Codex is a bit more stable in structure and shot control But both of them share one common problem: the performance of Sun Wukong the key character is not especially accurate Finally'

[12:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let’s talk about my recommendation If you just want to try the process you can start with the simplified version It is easier to run and better for getting familiar with the nodes and prompt structure If you want to make something closer to a product-ready result I recommend using the lossless version'

[12:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Because its base model is LTX two point three the execution speed is still very fast In this episode we basically covered three things First, we introduced this model which is mainly used for generating long videos'

[12:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Second we explained how to use it inside ComfyUI with two routes: the simplified version and the lossless version Third we focused on how prompts should be written including the rules you should follow when writing them manually'

[13:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and how to use large models to help write them We also compared three web coding tools along the way to see which one generates better prompts Alright, that’s all for today So what are you waiting for?'

[13:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go try it yourself Follow me and become someone who truly understands AI'
